Buff stoneware base with ridge and an incised circle on the bottom of the base. The edge of the base is bevelled. There are incised arcs on the exterior of the stoneware jar. There is a dip in the center of the base.
Body with incised swirl, lotus petal and line and arc designs.

Lug of a large jar. Design on the lug. Multiple vertical lines from the top of the lug  leading down to the motif of a taotie (monster/kala-head like) bottom of the lug. Taotie wears a elaborate crown-like crested head-dress and a wide open mouth showing teeth.Lug itself is 6.8x3.8.
Stylized monster mask (taotie) against a background of vertical lines over the lug. Light buff-brown glaze.

Taotie (monster mask) on the bottom portion of the lug. Vertical lines above the head. The mouth is not visible; the taotie has a prominent raised vertical crest above a prominent nose and two incised low relief bulging eyes.Lug itself is 5.5x3.7.
Lug is 4.1 x 2.2. Dark brown glaze on the exterior of the sherd.
Dark brown glaze on sgraffito buff brown sherd. Design comprises lines and wave lines.
Buff brown body with molded stamped motif of two dragon feet and claws and small portion of scaled underbelly. Purplish red wipe marks on the interior.
Stoneware jarlet with brown partial glaze on exterior. Everted downward turning rim profile.
Buff stoneware body with stamp Chinese character "qing xiang" (清香) [indicating sweet scent or fragrance].
Mouth of greyish buff stoneware with  pointed rim profile. Dark brown glaze on exterior and partial glaze on the interior just under the rim of the mouth.
Greyish buff stoneware sherd with Chinese stamp. The characters are zhen xin (朕新) [indicating good omen?]

Flaky mustard yellowish brownish glaze. Molded dragon decoration. The design is of the dragon head with one bulging eye, part of a upper lip, an ear, a horn and portion of its body.Yellowish buff clay body.

Grey body sherd with a Chinese character stamp design. Only one Chinese character and the top portion of the second character are visible. These appear to be bai hua (百花). The full stamp likely reads 百花香 ("Fragrance of 100 flowers").
Incised lines and lotus petals on exterior. White buff clay.

Incised lines on exterior in the form of lotus petal designs and incised lines. Two incised ridges in the area between neck and body. The interior of the sherd shows that the body and neck have been luted together. White buff clay. Similar to the previous entry: STABU0368.
Purplish red clay. No temper/inclusion.Potter's wheel marks on the interior. Flat base with a flanged protuding from it.Globular shaped body.

Black glaze on interior and exterior. Potter's wheel marks on interior. Flat bottom, glaze on the bottom of the base. A "dry ring" (no glaze around the bottom of the base. Purplish red clay body. Heavy vessel, dense and compact paste.

Mouth with semi-rolled lip. A flanged ring between the mouth and neck-body. Lug (3.1x1.7x0.9). Purplish red clay body.
Rolled rim of mouth. Potter's wheel marks on interior and exterior. Two intact lugs and one broken (4.1x1.2x0.7). Buff grey clay body.

Buff stoneware gacuk. Irregular edge.
Part of a large jar. A stamp with two Chinese characters next to the lug. The characters are nam he (南河). The characters are presented horizontally left to right.
Part of a Jarshoulder with stamp of two Chinese characters. The second character is largely not visible. The first character reads like a stylized yang (扬).
Bears a stamp with two Chinese characters ping xin (平心).
Stamp with two Chinese characters, with only the latter character present. The shape of the stamp is that of ancient Chinese knife money. The character is de (德).
Stamp with two Chinese characters presented horizontally; only the first character is visible: xi (熈).
Molded dragon design on the body of the sherd. The part of the motif visible is that of a portion of the dragon head: part of its mouth, cheek and eye and partial crown.
Glazed all the way to lower section of the body stopping short of the foot. Flat base, no footring. Everted mouth rim. Dark brown glaze.
Stamp containing one Chinese character: bao (寳).
Buff ware with reddish bisque. Wheel marks on the interior and exterior. For testing?

Decorative feature is that of the head of what looks like a Chinese lion comprising top of the head, the two bulging eyes, large snub nose with two flaring nostrils and the top lip of the mouth. It forms part of either a stand-alone figurine or may be a feature attached to something else.
Molded decoration on the body of a buff stoneware jar. Band with a series of circles, possibly representing part of a decoration which may be characteristic of dragon motif on buff stoneware jar.
Molded round bands with overlapping segmented tubular features like bamboo. Unglazed.
Sgraffito curved lines on the surface of the jar.
The body sherd contains stamped Chinese character: bao (宝).
Body contains a partial stamp, not enough to figure out what the character might have been.
Body with a stamp bearing two Chinese characters just beneath the neck of the vessel. The characters are: tong xin (通新).
Buff stoneware sherd with sgraffito design of swirls and wavy lines. Two pieces conjoined.

Buff stoneware with stamp containing two Chinese characters: si gong (司工). The first character appears to have been spelled wrongly. The term appears to have been used as an ancient Chinese court title, or possibly a division within an organization.
Buff stoneware sherd with a broken lug and a stamp showing two Chinese characters: chang xin (长新). The first character is presented in the complex script.
Lug and body sherd contains a stamp bearing two Chinese characters: qing xiang (清香). Lug (4.5x2.3x1.7).
